iddlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Preston, Gloucestershire, England":"Preston, Gloucestershire, England","Buried: Featherstone, Yorkshire, England":"Featherstone, Yorkshire, England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Preston on Stowe, Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Timbrell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Temporal","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Timbrell  ."]},{"name":"Timberell","meanings":["English:  see  Timbrell  ."]},{"name":"Timbrel","meanings":["English:  see  Timbrell  ."]}]},{"name":"Steven","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Stephen  , reflecting the normal pronunciation of the name in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Stephen","meanings":["Usual English spelling of the name of the first Christian martyr (Acts 6–7), whose feast is accordingly celebrated next after Christ's own (  26 December ). His name is derived from the Greek word <i>stephanos</i> ‘garland, crown’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":30,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":39,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":50,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":52,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":68,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":81,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Steven Timbrell was born in 1519, in Preston, Gloucestershire, England, his father, John Timbrell, was 19 and his mother, Alice 